The number of Kenyans who have tested positive for Covid-19 now stands at 51,851 after the Health Ministry announced 1,018 more new cases on Wednesday. The new cases were from a sample size of 6,649 tests conducted in 24 hours, representing a positivity rate of 15.3 per cent.  The rate was 20.5 per cent on Tuesday. In a statement, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said the new cases are 657 men and 361 women aged between nine months and 96 years. “Currently, there are 1,060 patients admitted in various health facilities countrywide while 4,230 are on home based isolation and care,” Kagwe said. “Thirty-six patients are in intensive care unit, 18 of whom are on ventilator support and 14 on supplemental oxygen. Forty-five patients are on supplementary oxygen, 22 or whom are in general wards and 23 are in High Dependency Unit.” The CS further confirmed that 16 more patients succumbed to the virus, raising the fatality in the country to 950. Similarly, 426 patients recovered from the disease, 312 from the home based care progrmamme while 114 were discharged from various hospitals across the country. The total number of recoveries in the country now stands at 35,258. In terms of distribution of cases per county, Nairobi recorded the highest number of cases after registering 199 infections, followed by Mombasa with 117, Kiambu with 102, Kericho with 73, Nakuru with 67, Bungoma 66, Uasin Gishu with 55 and Kisumu with 50. Kilifi recorded 40 new cases, Kisii 30, Bomet and Siaya 18 new cases each, Nyeri and West Pokot 16 cases each, Meru and Isiolo 14 cases each, Machakos 12 cases, Murang’a and Nandi 10 cases each while Laikipia, Kajiado and Garissa had nine cases each.